processing_method: mechanical alloying (MA) and spark plasma sintering (SPS)
evidence: An equi-atomic WNbMoTaV high entropy alloy (HEA) with a single body-centered cubic structure (BCC) was firstly fabricated by the powder metallurgical process of mechanical alloying (MA) and spark plasma sintering (SPS).

After 6 h of milling, nanocrystalline HEA powders were obtained with a crystallite size of 66.1 nm and a lattice strain of 0.96%. At 6 h of MA, the peaks of the principal elements had disappeared to leave three intense peaks located between those of pure W and Ta; these corresponded to a body-centered cubic (BCC) structure (PDF card no. 65-9439 for NbV).

microstructure: inhomogeneous dendritic; homogeneous with finer grains after MA and SPS; hexagonal oxide inclusions
evidence: The bulk specimen sintered at 1,500°C displayed an outstanding compressive yield strength of 2,612 MPa and a plastic strain of 8.8%. The yield strength of the WNbMoTaV HEA studied in this work was significantly enhanced over that of arc-melted and cast WNbMoTaV HEA, which has a yield strength of 1,246 MPa and an 80 μm grain size. The ultra-high mechanical properties of this alloy are attributed to the following effects: solid solution strengthening arising from a severe lattice distortion, which is an inherent characteristic of HEAs, solid solution strengthening by interstitial elements such as C and O, grain boundary strengthening governed by the Hall-Petch relationship and Orowan strengthening by oxide inclusions.

microstructure: BCC matrix with a small volume fraction of oxide inclusions
evidence: The bulk material sintered at 1,500°C had a compressive yield strength and plastic strain of 2,612 MPa and 8.8%, respectively, when measured at room temperature.
